1. Introduction

As students exploring R while also studying economics, we wanted to combine the two disciplines for our final project. In addition, having turned 18/19 ourselves in the past few years, we are now eligible to own credit cards under our own names, so we thought it would be interesting to see what factors affect the acceptance of a credit card application. In this project, we specifically look at the relationship between credit card application acceptance and variables such as average monthly credit card expenditure, the age of the applicant, their yearly income, the number of dependents they have, whether they own a home or not, the number of months living at their current address, the number of active credit card accounts they have, and the number of major credit cards they hold. We hope that through this analysis, we gain a better understanding of how credit cards work for our future financial endeavors.

2. Data

List of Variables

Categorical Variables:

  • card: acceptance of credit card application
    • 1/yes if application is accepted, 0/no if it is not accepted
  • owner: whether applicant owns or rents their home
    • 1/yes if they are a homeowner, 0/no if they rent

Continuous Variables:

  • reports: number of major derogatory reports filed against them
  • age: n years plus twelfths of a year
  • income: yearly income in tens of thousands of dollars
  • dependents: number of dependents
  • expenditure: average monthly credit card expenditure in dollars
  • months: number of months living at their current address
  • active: the number of active credit card accounts
  • majorcards: the number of major credit cards

Data from: Link to Data

We noticed that the “age” variable was not in whole numbers, and it also included ages under 18 (which means that the applicant cannot own a credit card under their name OR that the response on the survey was wrong), so we took the floor of age and deleted the cases where age was under 18. The first boxplot shows that the median yearly income for homeowners is higher than that of non-homeowners (renters), which means that homeowners have on average higher yearly income. There are many outliers for both homeowners and renters. The first histogram shows us that the distribution of income is heavily right skewed, indicating that more people tend to have incomes that bunch around the lower end. We decided to take the log of income and make a boxplot and histogram. Here, the boxplot after transformation reveals that the log of median yearly income for homeowners is higher than that of renters, and there are fewer outliers. The histogram shows us that the distribution of log of income is still right skewed, but not as skewed as before the transformation.

Scatterplot:

We took the square root of both age and months because before the transformation, our plot did not appear to have a linear trend, which would be inappropriate for calculating correlation. After this transformation, there appears to be a relatively moderately positive correlation between square root age and square root months at current address. It appears that using the correlation function is appropriate now since there are no strong outliers that may be over influencing the correlations.

5. Basic Tests

Correlation

cor(df$sqrtage, df$sqrtmonths)
## [1] 0.4488386
cor.test(df$sqrtage, df$sqrtmonths)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  df$sqrtage and df$sqrtmonths
## t = 18.179, df = 1310, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4045459 0.4910305
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.4488386

The correlation between square root age and square root months at current address is positive and relatively moderately strong at 0.4488386, as the above scatterplot shows. Using a correlation test, the p-value is less than our alpha of .05 so we reject the null hypothesis that the correlation is 0, which means there is a significantly non-zero correlation.

Bootstrap Confidence Interval for Correlation:

N <- nrow(df)
n_samp <- 10000
corResults <- rep(NA, n_samp)

for(i in 1:n_samp){
  s <- sample(1:N, N , replace = T)
  fakeData <- df[s, ]
  corResults[i] <- cor(fakeData$sqrtage, fakeData$sqrtmonths)
}

ci_r <- quantile(corResults, c(.025, .975))

hist(corResults, col = "blue", main = "Bootstrapped Correlations", xlab = "Sample Correlation", breaks = 50)
abline(v = ci_r, lwd = 3, col = "red")
abline(v = cor.test(df$age, df$months)$conf.int, lwd = 3, col = "green", lty = 2)
legend("topright", c("Theoretical CI","Boot CI"), lwd = 3, col = c("green","red"), lty = c(2, 1))

Since our bootstrapped confidence interval does not include 0, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the correlation between square root age and square root months at current address is significantly non-zero. The bootstrapped confidence interval is considerably wider than the theoretical confidence interval, which indicates that there is less certainty with our bootstrapped interval.

T-Test:

t.test(df$expenditure ~ df$owner)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  df$expenditure by df$owner
## t = -3.2796, df = 1152.3, p-value = 0.00107
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -80.45405 -20.22400
## sample estimates:
##  mean in group no mean in group yes 
##          162.7552          213.0942

The p-value of 0.00107 is less than alpha level of 0.05, which means we reject the null hypothesis and there is a statistically significant difference in means of average monthly credit card expenditure between people who own their home and people who rent. We are 95% confident that the true difference in means between renters and homeowners is between -$20.22400 and -$80.45405 (avg monthly credit card expenditures).

Permutation Test

actualdiff <- median(df$expenditure[df$owner == "yes"]) -  median(df$expenditure[df$owner == "no"])

set.seed(1)
N <- 10000

diffvals <- rep(NA, N)
for (i in 1:N) {
  fakeOwner <- sample(df$owner)
  diffvals[i] <- median(df$expenditure[fakeOwner == "yes"]) -  median(df$expenditure[fakeOwner == "no"])
}

hist(diffvals, col = "lightyellow", main = "Difference in Expenditure Median by Owner Status Permutation", xlab = "Thousands of Dollars", breaks = 50)
abline(v = actualdiff, col="blue", lwd=3)
text(actualdiff - 2, 450, paste("Actual Diff in Medians =", round(actualdiff,2)), srt = 90, cex = .9)

mean(abs(diffvals) >= abs(actualdiff))
## [1] 1e-04

Since the p-value of finding the actual difference in our permutation test (0.0001) is less than our alpha of .05, we can reject the null hypothesis that there is no difference in the median of average credit card expenditure per month by owner status.

6. Multiple Regression

Description of Plan:

Through backwards stepwise multiple regression, we aim to predict log average credit card expenditure per month through other continuous variables (including transformations of age, income, dependents, active, and months). We will only analyze the data points in which expenditure is greater than 0 (ie. people who are regularly actually spending money on their credit cards). We excluded share (which is just expenditure / income) and reports, which appears to be too heavily right skewed with too many 0 data points. In addition, we excluded majorcards, which acts similarly to a categorical variable, as the below histogram shows.

hist(df$majorcards, xlab = "major cards", main = "Histogram of Major Cards", col = "Red", breaks = 25)

Results, Residual Plots, and Discussion

df1 <- df[df$expenditure > 0,]
df1$logexpenditure <- log(df1$expenditure)
df1$sqrtactive <- sqrt(df1$active)
df1 <- df1[,c("logexpenditure", "sqrtage", "logincome", "dependents", "sqrtactive", "sqrtmonths")]

hist(df1$logexpenditure, main = "Histogram of Log Expenditure Excluding 0", xlab = "Log of Expenditure", col = "lightyellow", breaks = 50)

sigcorr <- cor.mtest(df1, conf.level = .95)
corrplot.mixed(cor(df1), lower.col = "black", upper = "ellipse", tl.col = "black", order = "hclust", p.mat = sigcorr$p, sig.level = .05, tl.cex = .75)

pairsJDRS(df1)

# Final model after manual backwards stepwise regression
mod2 <- lm(logexpenditure ~ sqrtage + logincome, data = df1)
summary(mod2)

We conducted transformations in order to make our histograms of each predictor rather normally distributed in the pairs JDRS plot (we took the log of expenditure, square root of age, log of income, left dependents alone, square root of active, and square root of months). In our mixed corr plot, all of our variables either have a very slight positive correlation with one another or no significant one. Based on the pairs JDRS plot, we can see that square root age and square root months have a rather linear correlation, indicating we have a issue of multicollinearity. Otherwise, there appears to be no issues of multicollinearity since the correlation plots appear to be largely blobs so no two variables appear to predict each other. Our final regression model, which we end up with after manual backwards stepwise regression, predicts expenditure based on square root of age and log of income, with each being significant predictors (p value for sqrtage is 0.000527 and p value for logincome is 2.05x10^-15, which are both less than alpha = 0.05). As logincome increases, since our slope is 1.00515, the log expenditure also increases. On the other hand, as sqrtage increases, since the slope is -0.17337, the log expenditure decreases. These directions make sense because you spend more when you have more income and you spend less when you are older. The R-squared value is .0616, meaning 6.16% of the variation in log expenditure can be explained by the predictors. Our R-value is not very high; however, the fit of the model appears to be generally good since the normal quantile plot of studentized residuals is mostly linear, indicating our studentized residuals are rather normally distributed. The lower left part of the normal quantile plot appears to stray downwards due to the fact that people tend to spend at least a cetain amount on their credit card per month. In the fits vs studentized residuals plot, the points are randomly distributed with no significant evidence of a linear pattern, there appears to be no heteroskedasticity, and there appears to be only a few outliers with 2 strong ones (385 and 341) having a negative direction.

Whether or not you own your home is a significant predictor of whether your credit card is approved, since the p-value is much less than the alpha level of 0.05. The odds of having your credit card approved are about 2.1 times higher for people that own their own home, since the odds ratio is 2.112. The residual deviance is 1369.1, so the log-likelihood is -1369.1/2 = -684.55. This is the natural log of the likelihood of our data under our null hypothesis model.

8. ANOVA

For ANOVA, we decided to split the ages into three groups: 18-30, 31-49, and 50+ to compare the income between the three groups

df3 <- df
df3$agegroup <- rep(NA, nrow(df3))
df3$agegroup[df3$age %in% seq(18, 30)] <- "18-30"
df3$agegroup[df3$age %in% seq(31, 49)] <- "31-49"
df3$agegroup[df3$age >= 50] <- "50+"

boxplot(df3$logincome ~ df3$agegroup, main = "Boxplot of Log Income by Age Group", col = c("lightgreen", "lightblue", "lightpink"), xlab = "Age Group", ylab = "Log Income")

Since the ratio of the maximum standard deviation to the minimum standard deviation is less than 2, we can assume the variances across age groups are relatively the same. The p-value is less than 2x10^-16, which is less than alpha = 0.05, meaning that there is a statistically significant difference in means between our three age groups. The normal quantile plot of residuals is relatively linear with points lying within/near the blue dotted lines, which means our data is approximately normal. Looking at the fits v. studentized residuals, we see some outliers, no signs of significant heteroskedasticity, and no non-linear trends, which satisfies our ANOVA model assumptions. From our Tukey plot, the only CI that contains 0 is 50+ and 31-49, which shows that these groups do not have statistically significant differences in means, while the other ones do.

9. Conclusions and Summary

Throughout our analysis, we were able to find interesting relationship between the variables in our data. Looking at our graphics, we are able to make some initial inferences and see that homeowners tend to have higher incomes than non-homeowners, more people tend to have incomes on the lower end, and that there is generally a relatively positive correlation between square root age and square root months at current address. We were then able to calculate the correlation of sqrt age and sqrt months and use a correlation test to confirm that it is significantly non-zero. Our Bootstrap confidence interval also comes to the same conclusion. Our t-test then shows that there is a statistically significant difference in the means of credit card expenditure based on whether or not someone owns a home. Our permutation test comes to the same conclusion except instead of mean expenditure, we tested for median expenditure and found that it was statistically significantly different based on whether or not someone is a homeowner. Through multiple regression, we found that square root age and log income are significant predictors of credit card expenditure. Through logistic regression, we found that home ownership is a significant predictor of whether or not your credit card is approved with those owning their homes being more likely to be approved. We also used ANOVA to look at income between three age grous, and concluded that there was a statistically significant difference in means between our three age groups. Altogether, we gained various insights about credit card activity that we will be able to convert to practical knowledge as beginner credit card holders ourselves.
